‘Finnegans Wake’ - latest show of German artist Anselm Kiefer at White Cube. It is the third in a trilogy of similarly huge, ambitious, immersive, oppressive exhibitions. All the 3 exhibitions is based on James Joyce’s famously unreadable experimental novels. It’s an impenetrable work of puns and metaphors, synecdoches and illusions, solipsistic language and endless word plays. 

Be honest with you I read only the “Ulysses” and it was a little be hypnotic 🤯🤪 

Some lines from the book are scratched across the walls of Kiefer’s show in “golden room” - first time I saw Kiefer works in gold but it was very impressive…

Ai Weiwei and his LARGEST Lego work that he has ever created in the London @designmuseum 👾

Water Lilies #1 created from Lego is a recreation of one of the most famous paintings by French Impressionist Claude Monet. I always thought of the painting as a portrait of nature, but Monet’s lily pond was a construct- the ideal world. The same idea is used in Ai’s Lego version BUT WITH A DARK DOOR 🚪… to the real world and to the underground dugout where Ai and his father lived in forced exile in the 1960s.

The name of the exhibition in @designmuseum is MAKING SENSE. One of the most famous Chinese contemporary artist, documentarian, and activist Ai Weiwei is trying to tell us something about the state of the world. This exhibition is the first to present Ai’s work as a commentary on design and what it reveals about our changing values.

Last year I saw this work “Moments Contained” by Thomas J Price on @artbasel … Surprising to see it on Central Station in Rotterdam 🤷🏻‍♀️

P.S. About

Combining details and materials referencing classical ancient Greek, Roman, and Egyptian sculptures with subtleties observed from daily life, Thomas J Price explores societal expectations and assumptions, whilst considering the space created between the viewer and the work itself. Moments Contained reconfigures the same fictional character of Price’s nine-foot sculpture Reaching Out in a new scale and pose, highlighting further the subtle shifts in presentation and perception that resonate throughout the artist’s practice. Price purposefully chooses not to portray specific people but instead presents imaginary, constructed characters. His works focus our attention on the systemic marginalization inherent to public monuments, through the artist’s hybrid approach of traditional sculpting and intuitive digital technology.

Thomas J Price (born 1981 in London) has sought to dismantle the power structures propagated by traditional sculpture, prompting his viewers to question who society deems worthy of a monument. His psychological portraits, despite their scale, appear unassuming and instantly recognizable. Price lives and works in London.

CABINET OF FIJNSCHILDERS and their magical light 💡 and invisible brushstrokes 🖌️🧑🏻‍🎨

The term finschilder ('fine painter') refers to the technique of a group of Leiden artists who were active in the 17th and 18th century.

They were famed for their meticulous rendition of materials and surfaces in a lifelike way, applying such fine brushstrokes that the brushwork was almost invisible. 

Their founder, Gerrit Dou, was the best-paid artist in the Dutch Republic. 

The finschilders acquired a truly international reputation with painters from the Van Mieris family. 

Up until the mid-19th century, their intimate, refined cabinet pieces commanded the highest prices. Thereafter, their rather modest work received competition from the more expressive paintings of Rembrandt and his circle.

The Leiden fijnschilders group was a male affair, but women were a popular subject, as the paintings in this gallery demonstrate. The women they depicted represent two types: virtuous and decent next to excessive and dissolute.

RUSSIAN AVANT-GARDE is my favourite period in the history of Russian art 🖼️📚

The term covers many separate, but inextricably related, art movements that flourished at the time, including Suprematism, Constructivism, Russian Futurism, Cubo-Futurism, Zaum, Imaginism, and Neo-primitivism, Luchizm…

Avant-garde artists’ culture is best described in Wassily Kandinsky’s words: “There is no must in art because art is free”.  

The Russian Avant­-garde is a broad term used to describe the different trends in modern art that flourished during the period of the Russian Revolution, over the Russian Empire's dissolution and the Soviet Union's establishment. 

The movement appeared in the late 19th century and it reached its creative aperture during the first decades of the 20th century, before the emergence of Socialist Realism in the early 1930s.

GES-2 - it is not only the Art Center in the heart of Moscow. For me it is a symbol of the great decade in Moscow from 2012-2022. It was a time of innovation, construction, improvement, development and integration.

GES-2 was a power station on the Bolotnaya Embankment, in the Yakimanka District of Moscow. Originally launched in 1907, it was the second major power station built in Moscow. GES-2 operated from 1907 to 2014. After its closure, GES-2 was sold to the V-A-C Foundation, who initiated a restoration and renovation project to convert the main building and surrounding area into a new cultural venue for the city of Moscow. GES-2 was redesigned by Renzo Piano Building Workshop.

The hottest time is always when we are planning a new project: discussions, disputes, misunderstandings… Of course, because the curator and the artist must understand each other and have a lot in common but at the same time look at the situation from totally different angles. For the artist to find a curator, and for the curator to find his artist is one of the most important key on the path to success in the modern art world.

Dongdaemun Design Plaza is a major urban development landmark in Seoul, South Korea, designed by Zaha Hadid and Samoo, with a distinctively neofuturistic design characterized by the “powerful, curving forms of elongated structures.”

The DDP has been one of the main reasons for Seoul’s designation as the World Design Capital in 2010. Construction started in 2009, and it was officially inaugurated on March 21, 2014.

Zaha Hadid - the “Queen of curves in architecture “. She was an Iraqi-British architect, artist and designer, recognized as a major figure in architecture of the late-20th and early-21st centuries. Born in Baghdad, Iraq, Hadid studied mathematics as an undergraduate and then enrolled at the Architectural Association School of Architecture in 1972. In search of an alternative system to traditional architectural drawing, and influenced by Suprematism and the Russian avant-garde, Hadid adopted painting as a design tool and abstraction as an investigative principle to “reinvestigate the aborted and untested experiments of Modernism to unveil new fields of building.”

Hadid was the first woman to receive the Pritzker Architecture Prize, in 2004. ❤️

KWANG YOUNG CHUN - Korean Artist, dad of my friend @arti__young ! Thank for having me it was a pleasure meeting you and seeing your excellent work @museumground and your dad’s art 👏🏻🫰

KWANG YOUNG CHUN is a Korean artist who studied and lived his 20th in the US: “The American dream of the 1960s promised success and wealth, but the reality was that innocent youths were dying on battlefields. This was a country where democracy had flourished, but young people were being doomed to an unfair death.  Some were dragged into a meaningless war that ended their lives in a faraway jungle, while others absorbed themselves in antiwar campaigns and marijuana, crossing the boundary between freedom and dangerous self-indulgence.”

For the artist the triangular pieces wrapped in mulberry paper are basic units of information, the basic cells of a life that only exists in art, as well as in individual social events or historical facts. By attaching these pieces one by one to a two-dimensional surface, artist wanted to express how basic units of information can both create harmony and conflict. This became an important milestone in the long artistic journey to express the troubles of a modern man who is driven to a devastated life by materialism, endless competition, conflict, and destruction. After almost twenty years, he was now able to communicate with his own gestures and words.

Anish Kapoor and his breathtaking art works in Kukje Gallery, Seoul!

I will start with my favourite gallery…It is very difficult to express in words the emotions that I felt when I was in front of these sculptures. There is something very sensual, giant, heavy but at the same time like a ocean deep that takes you inside. 

♦️♦️◾️◾️
Four monolithic sculptures defy categorisation. Delicate gauze barely contains the building material mass that makes up these heaving objects, which suggest both geological formation and visceral anatomical form. Pigmented in the dense red and black that Kapoor is famous for, two titles of the works contain suggestive allusions to their inspiration: Shadow and Ingest.

⚫️◼️⬛️
Second best is Kapoor’s signature black pigmented objects. The black pigment absorbs not only light but also sound, as they sit silently, enclosed in their skin. As the edges of the object dissolve before our eyes, it becomes a skinless object, evoking a primal and destabilizing effect. This capacity of the object to contain both absence and presence is a leitmotif of Kapoor’s practice.

🩸🫀💥🔴🥩❤️‍🔥🛑📛
The abstract works rendered in oil paint, fibreglass and silicone, present raw embodied states of being that suggest both bloody guts and efflorescence. In these works, the paint seems to be strewn across the canvas and we sense in these depictions physical matter that has been subject to extreme forces blurring inside and outside and suggesting Kapoor’s ongoing concern with the porous boundaries of the body. 

These themes are continued in more discreet ways in the artist’s gouache works.

social_posts.post_text:
I am already in Dubai but must share with you this beauty of Korea and Seoul.

On the photos I am at the National Folk Museum of Korea located in Seoul. It uses replicas of historical objects to illustrate the history of traditional life of the Korean people.

The museum was established on 8 November 1945 by the U.S. Government and opened on 25 April 1946 at the City Administration Memorial Hall. 

The museum has over 98,000 artifacts and three main exhibition halls: "History of Korean People" features materials of everyday life in Korea from prehistoric times to the end of the Joseon Dynasty in 1910; "Korean Way of Life", which illustrates Korean villagers in ancient times; and "Life Cycle of the Koreans", which depicts the deep roots of Confucianism in Korean culture and how this ideology gave rise to most of the culture's customs.

Enjoy Korean fairy tale and hope to be back soon 🥢🇰🇷🫶

THE FRONT SIDE STRIKES THE MOST

THANK YOU REPRESSION 🙏🏻💜😂 

The Story with this photo liked and commented so many people that it must be posted. 
All my life is about capturing beautiful moments and by the way I don’t remember bad things I remember the most beautiful and happy moments…

And I just found out that there is Repression phenomenon/syndrome in psychology…when people really remember only a good things..I have that syndrome 💯💯💯💯💯💯 😂

P.S. Repression is a key concept of psychoanalysis, where it is understood as a defense mechanism that "ensures that what is unacceptable to the conscious mind, and would if recalled arouse anxiety, is prevented from entering into it." This is a natural external mechanism. We don’t completely forget the bad things – only the things that traumatized us. We don’t remember scandals, quarrels, dissatisfaction, but we remember all the good moments.

I became “Handala” at 36…

I first met Palestinian artist Saher Nassar just a couple months ago during the blockade and when 120 000 Armenians were exiled from Artsakh. He told me the story and the meaning behind the”Handala” series of art works and it touched my heart and I felt a connection and decided to purchase one piece for my art collection.

“Handala” is a depiction of a Palestinian child with his back turned, forever stuck at the same age when he was exiled from his homeland. Handala, became a symbol of resistance and outrage in the face of injustice. Sakher Nasar's “Handala” has the half-mortal side and the other half where he lives forever.

I hope that peace will soon come to the Palestine land and this devastating situation will end.

Praying for peace 🙏🏻🕊️🤍

Sepideh Ilsley is an internationally-recognised abstract artist, born in Iran, grew up in Sweden and based in Australia. Ilsley's contemplative discourse unveils a profound journey marked by an unyielding commitment to poetic expression and exploration, a lyrical testament to the passage of time, encapsulating fleeting moments in tangible shapes. 

The artist says: "I see my practice as a journey of expression and exploration. My shapes are like poetry to me. Snapshots of moments in time. I wish to evoke emotion with these lyrical pieces. I imagine how the audience can see their own story in the paintings, and that the names of the pieces can work as a trigger for the imagination of the viewer to interpret and read their own story into the works. Text and objects working together. I want to allow for emotion, thought and a physical experience. I want to engage the viewer so that its significance can exist beyond the painting itself."

We all know that our dreams are a reliable reflection of reality. And sometimes - a reliable prediction. This is based on the continuous work of our tireless subconscious and unmistakable intuition.
Therefore, artist Marusya takes her dreams as seriously as a traditional subject such as a landscape or portrait. Artist tells and even immerses us in the world of her dreams, without missing out on many important, even symbolic details. Which are so necessary in order to wake up happy. These are dreams written “from life.” All dreams presented here are real and dreamed by the artist shortly before the exhibition.
